# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: colloid-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] This motion pattern typically consists of random fluctuations in a particle's position inside a fluid sub-domain, followed by a relocation to another sub-domain.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Each relocation is followed by more fluctuations within the new closed volume.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] This pattern describes a fluid at thermal equilibrium, defined by a given temperature.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Within such a fluid, there exists no preferential direction of flow (as in transport phenomena).
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] More specifically, the fluid's overall linear and angular momenta remain null over time.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The kinetic energies of the molecular Brownian motions, together with those of molecular rotations and vibrations, sum up to the caloric component of a fluid's internal energy (the equipartition theorem).
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] This motion is named after the Scottish botanist Robert Brown, who first described the phenomenon in 1827, while looking through a microscope at pollen of the plant *Clarkia pulchella* immersed in water.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] In 1900, the French mathematician Louis Bachelier modeled the stochastic process now called Brownian motion in his doctoral thesis, The Theory of Speculation (Théorie de la spéculation), prepared under the supervision of Henri Poincaré.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Then, in 1905, theoretical physicist Albert Einstein published a paper in which he modelled the motion of the pollen particles as being moved by individual water molecules, making one of his first major scientific contributions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The direction of the force of atomic bombardment is constantly changing, and at different times the particle is hit more on one side than another, leading to the seemingly random nature of the motion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] This explanation of Brownian motion served as convincing evidence that atoms and molecules exist and was further verified experimentally by Jean Perrin in 1908.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Perrin was awarded the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1926 "for his work on the discontinuous structure of matter".
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The many-body interactions that yield the Brownian pattern cannot be solved by a model accounting for every involved molecule.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Consequently, only probabilistic models applied to molecular populations can be employed to describe it.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Two such models of the statistical mechanics, due to Einstein and Smoluchowski, are presented below.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Another, pure probabilistic class of models is the class of the stochastic process models.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] There exist sequences of both simpler and more complicated stochastic processes which converge (in the limit) to Brownian motion (see random walk and Donsker's theorem).
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The Roman philosopher-poet Lucretius' scientific poem *On the Nature of Things* (c.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] 60 BC) has a remarkable description of the motion of dust particles in verses 113–140 from Book II.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The formal scientific discovery of this phenomenon is credited to the botanist Robert Brown in 1827.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Brown was studying plant reproduction when he observed pollen grains of the plant *Clarkia pulchella* in water under a simple microscope.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] These grains contain minute particles on the order of 1/4,000th of an inch (6.4 microns) in size.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] He observed these particles executing a continuous, jittery motion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] By repeating the experiment with particles of inorganic matter, such as glass and rock dust, he was able to rule out that the motion was life-related, although its physical origin was yet to be explained.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The mathematics of much of stochastic analysis, including the mathematics of Brownian motion, was introduced by Louis Bachelier in 1900 in his PhD thesis "The theory of speculation", in which he presented an innovative probabilistic analysis of the stock and option markets.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] However, this pioneering mathematical work connecting random walks to continuous time was largely unknown until the 1950s.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The instantaneous velocity of the Brownian motion can be defined as *v* = Δ*x*/Δ*t*, when Δ*t* << *τ*, where τ is the momentum relaxation time.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] In this way Einstein was able to determine the size of atoms, and how many atoms there are in a mole, or the molecular weight in grams, of a gas.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] In accordance to Avogadro's law, this volume is the same for all ideal gases, namely 22.414 liters at standard temperature and pressure.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The first part of Einstein's argument was to determine how far a Brownian particle travels in a given time interval.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Classical mechanics is unable to determine this distance because of the enormous number of bombardments a Brownian particle will undergo, roughly of the order of 1014 collisions per second.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The integral in the first term is equal to one by the definition of probability, and the second and other even terms (i.e. first and other odd moments) vanish because of space symmetry.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The first moment is seen to vanish, meaning that the Brownian particle is equally likely to move to the left as it is to move to the right.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The second moment is, however, non-vanishing, being given by $\mathbb {E} {\left[x^{2}\right]}=2Dt.$ This equation expresses the mean squared displacement in terms of the time elapsed and the diffusivity.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] From this expression Einstein argued that the displacement of a Brownian particle is not proportional to the elapsed time, but rather to its square root.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] His argument is based on a conceptual switch from the "ensemble" of Brownian particles to the "single" Brownian particle: we can speak of the relative number of particles at a single instant just as well as of the time it takes a Brownian particle to reach a given point.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The second part of Einstein's theory relates the diffusion constant to physically measurable quantities, such as the mean squared displacement of a particle in a given time interval.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] This result enables the experimental determination of the Avogadro number and therefore the size of molecules.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Einstein analyzed a dynamic equilibrium being established between opposing forces.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The beauty of his argument is that the final result does not depend upon which forces are involved in setting up the dynamic equilibrium.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] In his original treatment, Einstein considered an osmotic pressure experiment, but the same conclusion can be reached in other ways.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Consider, for instance, particles suspended in a viscous fluid in a gravitational field.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Gravity tends to make the particles settle, whereas diffusion acts to homogenize them, driving them into regions of smaller concentration.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Under the action of gravity, a particle acquires a downward speed of *v* = *μmg*, where m is the mass of the particle, g is the acceleration due to gravity, and μ is the particle's mobility in the fluid.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] George Stokes had shown that the mobility for a spherical particle with radius r is $\mu ={\tfrac {1}{6\pi \eta r}}$ , where η is the dynamic viscosity of the fluid.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Dynamic equilibrium is established because the more that particles are pulled down by gravity, the greater the tendency for the particles to migrate to regions of lower concentration.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The flux is given by Fick's law, $J=-D{\frac {d\rho }{dh}},$ where *J* = *ρv*.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] In a state of dynamical equilibrium, this speed must also be equal to *v* = *μmg*.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Both expressions for v are proportional to *mg*, reflecting that the derivation is independent of the type of forces considered.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Similarly, one can derive an equivalent formula for identical charged particles of charge q in a uniform electric field of magnitude E, where *mg* is replaced with the electrostatic force *qE*.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] By measuring the mean squared displacement over a time interval along with the universal gas constant *R*, the temperature T, the viscosity η, and the particle radius r, the Avogadro constant *N*A can be determined.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The type of dynamical equilibrium proposed by Einstein was not new.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] It had been pointed out previously by J.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] An identical expression to Einstein's formula for the diffusion coefficient was also found by Walther Nernst in 1888 in which he expressed the diffusion coefficient as the ratio of the osmotic pressure to the ratio of the frictional force and the velocity to which it gives rise.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The former was equated to the law of van 't Hoff while the latter was given by Stokes's law.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] He writes $k'=p_{o}/k$ for the diffusion coefficient k′, where $p_{o}$ is the osmotic pressure and k is the ratio of the frictional force to the molecular viscosity which he assumes is given by Stokes's formula for the viscosity.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Introducing the ideal gas law per unit volume for the osmotic pressure, the formula becomes identical to that of Einstein's.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The use of Stokes's law in Nernst's case, as well as in Einstein and Smoluchowski, is not strictly applicable since it does not apply to the case where the radius of the sphere is small in comparison with the mean free path.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Confirming Einstein's formula experimentally proved difficult.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Initial attempts by Theodor Svedberg in 1906 and 1907 were critiqued by Einstein and by Perrin as not measuring a quantity directly comparable to the formula.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Victor Henri in 1908 took cinematographic shots through a microscope and found quantitative disagreement with the formula but again the analysis was uncertain.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Einstein's predictions were finally confirmed in a series of experiments carried out by Chaudesaigues in 1908 and Perrin in 1909.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The confirmation of Einstein's theory constituted empirical progress for the kinetic theory of heat.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] In essence, Einstein showed that the motion can be predicted directly from the kinetic model of thermal equilibrium.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The importance of the theory lay in the fact that it confirmed the kinetic theory's account of the second law of thermodynamics as being an essentially statistical law.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Smoluchowski's theory of Brownian motion, later contextualized in comprehensive reviews of stochastic physics, starts from the same premise as that of Einstein and derives the same probability distribution *ρ*(*x*, *t*) for the displacement of a Brownian particle along the x axis in time t.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] He therefore gets the same expression for the mean squared displacement: ${\textstyle \mathbb {E} {\left[(\Delta x)^{2}\right]}}$ .
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Associating the kinetic energy ${\textstyle mu^{2}/2}$ with the thermal energy ${\textstyle RT/N}$ , the expression for the mean squared displacement is 64/27 times that found by Einstein.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Smoluchowski attempts to answer the question of why a Brownian particle should be displaced by bombardments of smaller particles when the probabilities for striking it in the forward and rear directions are exactly equal.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] $\mathbb {E} {\left[2m-n\right]}\approx {\sqrt {\frac {n}{2\pi }}}$ showing that the net displacement increases proportionally to the square root of the total population of collision events.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Suppose that a Brownian particle of mass M is surrounded by lighter particles of mass m which are traveling at a speed u.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] These orders of magnitude do not take into consideration the velocity of the Brownian particle, U, which actively depends on the collisions that tend to accelerate and decelerate it.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The larger U is, the greater will be the resistive drag of collisions that will retard it, so that the velocity of a Brownian particle can never increase without limit.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] If such an unbounded process could occur, it would be tantamount to a perpetual motion machine of the second kind.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Since the equipartition of energy applies to this system in thermal equilibrium, the kinetic energy of the Brownian particle, ${\textstyle MU^{2}/2}$ , will be equal, on the average, to the kinetic energy of the surrounding fluid particle, ${\textstyle mu^{2}/2}$ .
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] In 1906, Smoluchowski published a one-dimensional model to describe a particle undergoing Brownian motion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The model assumes collisions with ${\textstyle M\gg m}$ where M is the test particle's mass and m the mass of one of the individual particles composing the fluid.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] If ${\textstyle N_{\text{R}}}$ is the number of collisions from the right and ${\textstyle N_{\text{L}}}$ the number of collisions from the left then after N collisions the particle's velocity will have changed by ${\textstyle \Delta V(2N_{\text{R}}-N)}$ .
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The multiplicity is then simply given by: ${\binom {N}{N_{\text{R}}}}={\frac {N!}{N_{\text{R}}!(N-N_{\text{R}})!}}$ and the total number of possible states is given by ${\textstyle 2^{N}}$ .
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] As a result of its simplicity, Smoluchowski's 1D model can only qualitatively describe Brownian motion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] For a realistic particle undergoing Brownian motion in a fluid, many of the assumptions do not apply.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] For example, the assumption that on average there are an equal number of collisions from the right as from the left falls apart once the particle is in motion, as it will sweep into particles in its path and create a velocity-dependent drag force.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Furthermore, there would be a continuous statistical distribution of different possible ${\textstyle \Delta V}$ s governed by the Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution of fluid molecule velocities, rather than a single discrete value in a physical liquid or gas.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The diffusion equation yields an approximation of the time evolution of the probability density function associated with the position of the particle going under a Brownian movement under the physical definition.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The approximation becomes valid on timescales much larger than the timescale of individual atomic collisions, since it does not include a term to describe the acceleration of particles during collision.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The time evolution of the position of the Brownian particle over all time scales described using the Langevin equation, an equation that involves a random force field representing the effect of the thermal fluctuations of the solvent on the particle.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] At longer times scales, where acceleration is negligible, individual particle dynamics can be approximated using Brownian dynamics in place of Langevin dynamics.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] In stellar dynamics, a massive body (star, black hole, etc.) can experience Brownian motion as it responds to gravitational forces from surrounding stars.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The rms velocity V of the massive object, of mass M, is related to the rms velocity $v_{\star }$ of the background stars by $MV^{2}\approx mv_{\star }^{2}$ where $m\ll M$ is the mass of the background stars.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The gravitational force from the massive object causes nearby stars to move faster than they otherwise would, increasing both $v_{\star }$ and V.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The Brownian velocity of Sgr A*, the supermassive black hole at the center of the Milky Way galaxy, is predicted from this formula to be less than 1 km s−1.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] In mathematics, Brownian motion is described by the **Wiener process**, a continuous-time stochastic process named in honor of Norbert Wiener.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] It is one of the best known Lévy processes (càdlàg stochastic processes with stationary independent increments) and occurs frequently in pure and applied mathematics, economics and physics.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] ${\mathcal {N}}(\mu ,\sigma ^{2})$ denotes the normal distribution with expected value μ and variance *σ*2.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] In addition, for some filtration ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ , $W_{t}$ is ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ measurable for all $t\geq 0$ .
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] An alternative characterisation of the Wiener process is the so-called *Lévy characterisation* that says that the Wiener process is an almost surely continuous martingale with *W*0 = 0 and quadratic variation $[W_{t},W_{t}]=t$ .
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] A third characterisation is that the Wiener process has a spectral representation as a sine series whose coefficients are independent ${\mathcal {N}}(0,1)$ random variables.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] This representation can be obtained using the Kosambi–Karhunen–Loève theorem.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The Wiener process can be constructed as the scaling limit of a random walk, or other discrete-time stochastic processes with stationary independent increments.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Like the random walk, the Wiener process is recurrent in one or two dimensions (meaning that it returns almost surely to any fixed neighborhood of the origin infinitely often) whereas it is not recurrent in dimensions three and higher.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Unlike the random walk, it is scale invariant.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The Brownian motion can be modeled by a random walk.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] In the general case, Brownian motion is a Markov process and described by stochastic integral equations.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The French mathematician Paul Lévy proved the following theorem, which gives a necessary and sufficient condition for a continuous **R***n*-valued stochastic process *X* to actually be n-dimensional Brownian motion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Hence, Lévy's condition can actually be used as an alternative definition of Brownian motion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Let *X* = (*X*1, ..., *X**n*) be a continuous stochastic process on a probability space (Ω, Σ, **P**) taking values in **R***n*.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] 2. for all 1 ≤ *i*, *j* ≤ *n*, *X**i*(*t*) *X**j*(*t*) − *δ**ij* *t* is a martingale with respect to **P** (and its own natural filtration), where *δ**ij* denotes the Kronecker delta.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The spectral content of a stochastic process $X_{t}$ can be found from the power spectral density, formally defined as $S(\omega )=\lim _{T\to \infty }{\frac {1}{T}}\mathbb {E} \left\{\left|\int _{0}^{T}e^{i\omega t}X_{t}dt\right|^{2}\right\},$ where $\mathbb {E}$ stands for the expected value.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The power spectral density of Brownian motion is found to be $S_{BM}(\omega )={\frac {4D}{\omega ^{2}}}.$ where D is the diffusion coefficient of *Xt*.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] For sufficiently long realization times, the expected value of the power spectrum of a single trajectory converges to the formally defined power spectral density $S(\omega )$ , but its coefficient of variation $\gamma =\sigma /\mu$ tends to ${\sqrt {5}}/2$ .
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] This implies the distribution of $S^{(1)}(\omega ,T)$ is broad even in the infinite time limit.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Brownian motion is usually considered to take place in Euclidean space.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] It is natural to consider how such motion generalizes to more complex shapes, such as surfaces or higher dimensional manifolds.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The formalization requires the space to possess some form of a derivative, as well as a metric, so that a Laplacian can be defined.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Both of these are available on Riemannian manifolds.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Riemannian manifolds have the property that geodesics can be described in polar coordinates; that is, displacements are always in a radial direction, at some given angle.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Uniform random motion is then described by Gaussians along the radial direction, independent of the angle, the same as in Euclidean space.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The infinitesimal generator (and hence characteristic operator) of Brownian motion on Euclidean **R***n* is ⁠1/2⁠Δ, where Δ denotes the Laplace operator.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] Brownian motion on an m-dimensional Riemannian manifold (*M*, *g*) can be defined as diffusion on M with the characteristic operator given by ⁠1/2⁠ΔLB, half the Laplace–Beltrami operator ΔLB.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] One of the topics of study is a characterization of the Poincaré recurrence time for such systems.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] The narrow escape problem is that of calculating the mean escape time.
[src:colloid-chemistry/brownian-motion] This time diverges as the window shrinks, thus rendering the calculation a singular perturbation problem.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] A **colloid** is a mixture in which one substance, consisting of microscopically dispersed insoluble particles, is suspended throughout another substance.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Some definitions specify that the particles must be dispersed in a liquid, while others extend the definition to include substances like aerosols and gels.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] The term **colloidal suspension** refers unambiguously to the overall mixture (although a narrower sense of the word *suspension* is distinguished from colloids by larger particle size).
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] A colloid has a dispersed phase (the suspended particles) and a continuous phase (the medium of suspension).
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Some colloids are translucent because of the Tyndall effect, which is the scattering of light by particles in the colloid.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Other colloids may be opaque or have a slight color.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Colloidal suspensions are the subject of interface and colloid science.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] This field of study began in 1845 with Francesco Selmi, who called them pseudosolutions, and was later expanded by Michael Faraday and Thomas Graham, who coined the term *colloid* in 1861.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] This IUPAC definition is particularly important because it highlights the flexibility inherent in colloidal systems.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] However, much of the confusion surrounding colloids arises from oversimplifications.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] IUPAC makes it clear that exceptions exist, and the definition should not be viewed as a rigid rule.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Everett—the scientist who wrote the IUPAC definition—emphasized that colloids are often better understood through examples rather than strict definitions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Homogeneous mixtures with a dispersed phase in this size range may be called *colloidal aerosols*, *colloidal emulsions*, *colloidal suspensions*, *colloidal foams*, *colloidal dispersions*, or *hydrosols*.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] The term *hydrocolloid* may also refer to a type of wound dressing, designed to lock moisture in the skin and help the natural healing process of skin, to reduce scarring, itching, and soreness.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Hydrocolloids contain some type of gel-forming agent, such as sodium carboxymethylcellulose (NaCMC) or gelatin.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] They are normally combined with some type of sealant, like polyurethane, to stick to skin.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] A colloid has a dispersed phase and a continuous phase, whereas in a solution, the solute and solvent constitute only one phase.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] A solute in a solution are individual molecules or ions, whereas colloidal particles are bigger.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] For example, in a solution of salt in water, the sodium chloride (NaCl) crystal dissolves, and the Na+ and Cl− ions are surrounded by water molecules.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] However, in a colloid such as milk, the colloidal particles are globules of fat, rather than individual fat molecules.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Because colloid is multiple phases, it has very different properties compared to fully mixed, continuous solution.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] The Earth's gravitational field acts upon colloidal particles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Therefore, if the colloidal particles are denser than the medium of suspension, they will sediment (fall to the bottom), or if they are less dense, they will cream (float to the top).
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Larger particles also have a greater tendency to sediment because they have smaller Brownian motion to counteract this movement.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] and v is the sedimentation or creaming velocity.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] and $\rho _{1}-\rho _{2}$ is the difference in mass density between the colloidal particle and the suspension medium.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] There is an upper limit on the diameter of colloidal particles, because particles larger than 1 μm tend to sediment; thus, the substance would no longer be considered a colloidal suspension.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] The colloidal particles are said to be in sedimentation equilibrium, if the rate of sedimentation is equal to the rate of movement from Brownian motion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] The stability of a colloidal system is defined by particles remaining suspended in solution and depends on the interaction forces between the particles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] These include electrostatic interactions and van der Waals forces, because they both contribute to the overall free energy of the system.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] A colloid is stable if the interaction energy due to attractive forces between the colloidal particles is less than kT, where k is the Boltzmann constant and T is the absolute temperature.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] If this is the case, then the colloidal particles will repel or only weakly attract each other, and the substance will remain a suspension.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] If the interaction energy is greater than kT, the attractive forces will prevail, and the colloidal particles will begin to clump together.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] This process is referred to generally as aggregation, but is also referred to as flocculation, coagulation or precipitation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] While these terms are often used interchangeably, for some definitions they have slightly different meanings.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] For example, coagulation can be used to describe irreversible, permanent aggregation where the forces holding the particles together are stronger than any external forces caused by stirring or mixing.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Flocculation can be used to describe reversible aggregation involving weaker attractive forces, and the aggregate is usually called a *floc*.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] The term precipitation is normally reserved for describing a phase change from a colloid dispersion to a solid (precipitate) when it is subjected to a perturbation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Aggregation causes sedimentation or creaming, therefore the colloid is unstable: if either of these processes occur the colloid will no longer be a suspension.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Electrostatic stabilization and steric stabilization are the two main mechanisms for stabilization against aggregation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] A combination of the two mechanisms is also possible (electrosteric stabilization).
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] A method called gel network stabilization represents the principal way to produce colloids stable to both aggregation and sedimentation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] The method consists in adding to the colloidal suspension a polymer able to form a gel network.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Particle settling is hindered by the stiffness of the polymeric matrix where particles are trapped, and the long polymeric chains can provide a steric or electrosteric stabilization to dispersed particles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Examples of such substances are xanthan and guar gum.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Unstable colloidal suspensions of low-volume fraction form clustered liquid suspensions, wherein individual clusters of particles sediment if they are more dense than the suspension medium, or cream if they are less dense.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] However, colloidal suspensions of higher-volume fraction form colloidal gels with viscoelastic properties.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Viscoelastic colloidal gels, such as bentonite and toothpaste, flow like liquids under shear, but maintain their shape when shear is removed.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] It is for this reason that toothpaste can be squeezed from a toothpaste tube, but stays on the toothbrush after it is applied.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] The most widely used technique to monitor the dispersion state of a product, and to identify and quantify destabilization phenomena, is multiple light scattering coupled with vertical scanning.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] This method, known as turbidimetry, is based on measuring the fraction of light that, after being sent through the sample, is backscattered by the colloidal particles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] The backscattering intensity is directly proportional to the average particle size and volume fraction of the dispersed phase.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Therefore, local changes in concentration caused by sedimentation or creaming, and clumping together of particles caused by aggregation, are detected and monitored.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] These phenomena are associated with unstable colloids.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Dynamic light scattering can be used to detect the size of a colloidal particle by measuring how fast they diffuse.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] This method involves directing laser light towards a colloid.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] The scattered light will form an interference pattern, and the fluctuation in light intensity in this pattern is caused by the Brownian motion of the particles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] If the apparent size of the particles increases due to them clumping together via aggregation, it will result in slower Brownian motion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] This technique can confirm that aggregation has occurred if the apparent particle size is determined to be beyond the typical size range for colloidal particles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] The kinetic process of destabilisation can be rather long (up to several months or years for some products).
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Thus, further accelerating methods are often required, to enable the formulator to develop a new product design within a reasonable timeframe.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Thermal methods are the most commonly used and consist of increasing temperature to accelerate destabilisation (below critical temperatures of phase inversion or chemical degradation).
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Temperature affects not only viscosity, but also interfacial tension in the case of non-ionic surfactants or more generally interactions forces inside the system.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Storing a dispersion at high temperatures makes it possible to simulate real-life conditions for a product (e.g. tube of sunscreen cream in a car in the summer), but also to accelerate destabilisation processes up to 200 times.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Mechanical acceleration including vibration, centrifugation and agitation are sometimes used.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] They subject the product to different forces that pushes the particles / droplets against one another, hence helping in the film drainage.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Some emulsions would never coalesce in normal gravity, while they do under artificial gravity.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Segregation of different populations of particles have been highlighted when using centrifugation and vibration.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] In physics, colloids are an interesting model system for atoms.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Micrometre-scale colloidal particles are large enough to be observed by optical techniques such as confocal microscopy.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Many of the forces that govern the structure and behavior of matter, such as excluded volume interactions or electrostatic forces, govern the structure and behavior of colloidal suspensions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] For example, the same techniques used to model ideal gases can be applied to model the behavior of a hard sphere colloidal suspension.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Phase transitions in colloidal suspensions can be studied in real time using optical techniques, and are analogous to phase transitions in liquids.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] In many interesting cases optical fluidity is used to control colloid suspensions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Colloids are also used as model systems for studying the glass transition, because dense colloidal suspensions can display glassy dynamics similar to those of glass-forming liquids.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Molecular-dynamics simulations of anisotropic ellipsoidal particles interacting through the Gay–Berne potential have reported liquid-glass behavior related to experiments on ellipsoidal PMMA colloids, where rotational motion becomes arrested while translational motion remains fluid-like.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] A colloidal crystal is a highly ordered array of particles that can be formed over a very long range (typically on the order of a few millimeters to one centimeter) and that appear analogous to their atomic or molecular counterparts.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] One of the finest natural examples of this ordering phenomenon can be found in precious opal, in which brilliant regions of pure spectral color result from close-packed domains of amorphous colloidal spheres of silicon dioxide (or silica, SiO2).
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] These spherical particles precipitate in highly siliceous pools in Australia and elsewhere, and form these highly ordered arrays after years of sedimentation and compression under hydrostatic and gravitational forces.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] The periodic arrays of submicrometre spherical particles provide similar arrays of interstitial voids, which act as a natural diffraction grating for visible light waves, particularly when the interstitial spacing is of the same order of magnitude as the incident lightwave.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] In all of these cases in nature, the same brilliant iridescence (or play of colors) can be attributed to the diffraction and constructive interference of visible lightwaves that satisfy Bragg's law, in a matter analogous to the scattering of X-rays in crystalline solids.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Colloidal phase separation is an important organising principle for compartmentalisation of both the cytoplasm and nucleus of cells into **biomolecular condensates**—similar in importance to compartmentalisation via lipid bilayer membranes, a type of liquid crystal.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] The term biomolecular condensate has been used to refer to clusters of macromolecules that arise via liquid-liquid or liquid-solid phase separation within cells.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Macromolecular crowding strongly enhances colloidal phase separation and formation of biomolecular condensates.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Colloidal solutions are also used as a tool enabling fast, simple, and safe intracellular delivery of various types of molecules, such as polymers or proteins.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Colloidal particles can also serve as transport vectors of diverse contaminants in the surface water (sea water, lakes, rivers, freshwater bodies) and in underground water circulating in fissured rocks (e.g. limestone, sandstone, granite).
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Radionuclides and heavy metals easily sorb onto colloids suspended in water.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Various types of colloids are recognised: inorganic colloids (e.g. clay particles, silicates, iron oxy-hydroxides), organic colloids (humic and fulvic substances).
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] When heavy metals or radionuclides form pure colloids, the term "*eigencolloid*" is used to designate pure phases, i.e., pure Tc(OH)4, U(OH)4, or Am(OH)3.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Colloids have been suspected for the long-range transport of plutonium on the Nevada Nuclear Test Site.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] They have been the subject of detailed studies for many years.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] However, the mobility of inorganic colloids is very low in compacted bentonites and in deep clay formations because of the process of ultrafiltration occurring in dense clay membrane.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] The question is less clear for small organic colloids often mixed in porewater with truly dissolved organic molecules.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] In soil science, the colloidal fraction in soils consists of tiny clay and humus particles that are less than 1μm in diameter and carry either positive and/or negative electrostatic charges that vary depending on the chemical conditions of the soil sample, i.e. soil pH.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Colloid solutions used in intravenous therapy belong to a major group of volume expanders, and can be used for intravenous fluid replacement.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Colloids preserve a high colloid osmotic pressure in the blood, and therefore, they should theoretically preferentially increase the intravascular volume, whereas other types of volume expanders called crystalloids also increase the interstitial volume and intracellular volume.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] However, there is still controversy to the actual difference in efficacy by this difference, and much of the research related to this use of colloids is based on fraudulent research by Joachim Boldt.
[src:colloid-chemistry/colloid] Another difference is that crystalloids generally are much cheaper than colloids.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] An **emulsion** is a mixture of two or more liquids that are normally immiscible (unmixable or unblendable) owing to liquid-liquid phase separation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Emulsions are part of a more general class of two-phase systems of matter called colloids.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Although the terms *colloid* and *emulsion* are sometimes used interchangeably, *emulsion* more narrowly refers to when both phases, dispersed and continuous, are liquids.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] In an emulsion, one liquid (the dispersed phase) is dispersed in the other (the continuous phase).
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Examples of emulsions include vinaigrettes, homogenized milk, liquid biomolecular condensates, and some cutting fluids for metal working.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Two liquids can form different types of emulsions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] As an example, oil and water can form, first, an oil-in-water emulsion, in which the oil is the dispersed phase, and water is the continuous phase.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Second, they can form a water-in-oil emulsion, in which water is the dispersed phase and oil is the continuous phase.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Multiple emulsions are also possible, including a "water-in-oil-in-water" emulsion and an "oil-in-water-in-oil" emulsion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Emulsions, being liquids, do not exhibit a static internal structure.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The droplets dispersed in the continuous phase (sometimes referred to as the "dispersion medium") are usually assumed to be statistically distributed to produce roughly spherical droplets.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The term "emulsion" is also used to refer to the photo-sensitive side of photographic film.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Such a photographic emulsion consists of silver halide colloidal particles dispersed in a gelatin matrix.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Nuclear emulsions are similar to photographic emulsions, except that they are used in particle physics to detect high-energy elementary particles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Whilst an emulsion roughly corresponds to a mixture of at least two immiscible liquids mixed together, by contrast **emulsification** is the process of dispersing two or more immiscible liquids together through the use of an emulsifier (e.g., lecithin in a mixture of oil and water).
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Nanoemulsification is the process of emulsification in the nanoscale.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] A nanoemulsion is a particular kind of emulsion, with droplet sizes on the order of 100 nm.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The word *emulsion* comes from the Latin *emulgere* 'to milk out', from *ex* 'out' + *mulgere* 'to milk', as milk is an emulsion of fat and water, along with other components, including colloidal casein micelles (a type of secreted biomolecular condensate).
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Emulsions contain both a dispersed and a continuous phase, with the boundary between the phases called the "interface".
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Emulsions tend to have a cloudy appearance because the many phase interfaces scatter light as it passes through the emulsion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Emulsions appear white when all light is scattered equally.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] If the emulsion is dilute enough, higher-frequency (shorter-wavelength) light will be scattered more, and the emulsion will appear bluer – this is called the "Tyndall effect".
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] If the emulsion is concentrated enough, the color will be distorted toward comparatively longer wavelengths, and will appear more yellow.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] This phenomenon is easily observable when comparing skimmed milk, which contains little fat, to cream, which contains a much higher concentration of milk fat.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Two special classes of emulsions – microemulsions and nanoemulsions, with droplet sizes below 100 nm – appear translucent.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] This property is due to the fact that light waves are scattered by the droplets only if their sizes exceed about one-quarter of the wavelength of the incident light.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Since the visible spectrum of light is composed of wavelengths between 390 and 750 nanometers (nm), if the droplet sizes in the emulsion are below about 100 nm, the light can penetrate through the emulsion without being scattered.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Due to their similarity in appearance, translucent nanoemulsions and microemulsions are frequently confused.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Unlike translucent nanoemulsions, which require specialized equipment to be produced, microemulsions are spontaneously formed by "solubilizing" oil molecules with a mixture of surfactants, co-surfactants, and co-solvents.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The required surfactant concentration in a microemulsion is, however, several times higher than that in a translucent nanoemulsion, and significantly exceeds the concentration of the dispersed phase.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Because of many undesirable side-effects caused by surfactants, their presence is disadvantageous or prohibitive in many applications.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] In addition, the stability of a microemulsion is often easily compromised by dilution, by heating, or by changing pH levels.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Common emulsions are inherently unstable and, thus, do not tend to form spontaneously.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Energy input – through shaking, stirring, homogenizing, or exposure to powerful ultrasound – is needed to form an emulsion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Over time, emulsions tend to revert to the stable state of the phases comprising the emulsion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] An example of this is seen in the separation of the oil and vinegar components of vinaigrette, an unstable emulsion that will quickly separate unless shaken almost continuously.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] There are important exceptions to this rule – microemulsions are thermodynamically stable, while translucent nanoemulsions are kinetically stable.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Whether an emulsion of oil and water turns into a "water-in-oil" emulsion or an "oil-in-water" emulsion depends on the volume fraction of both phases and the type of emulsifier (surfactant) (see *Emulsifier*, below) present.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Emulsion stability refers to the ability of an emulsion to resist change in its properties over time.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] There are four types of instability in emulsions: flocculation, coalescence, creaming/sedimentation, and Ostwald ripening.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Flocculation occurs when there is an attractive force between the droplets, so they form flocs, like bunches of grapes.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] This process can be desired, if controlled in its extent, to tune physical properties of emulsions such as their flow behaviour.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Coalescence occurs when droplets bump into each other and combine to form a larger droplet, so the average droplet size increases over time.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Emulsions can also undergo creaming, where the droplets rise to the top of the emulsion under the influence of buoyancy, or under the influence of the centripetal force induced when a centrifuge is used.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Creaming is a common phenomenon in dairy and non-dairy beverages (i.e. milk, coffee milk, almond milk, soy milk) and usually does not change the droplet size.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Sedimentation is the opposite phenomenon of creaming and normally observed in water-in-oil emulsions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Sedimentation happens when the dispersed phase is denser than the continuous phase and the gravitational forces pull the denser globules towards the bottom of the emulsion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Similar to creaming, sedimentation follows Stokes' law.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] An appropriate surface active agent (or surfactant) can increase the kinetic stability of an emulsion so that the size of the droplets does not change significantly with time.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The stability of an emulsion, like a suspension, can be studied in terms of zeta potential, which indicates the repulsion between droplets or particles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] If the size and dispersion of droplets does not change over time, it is said to be stable.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] For example, oil-in-water emulsions containing mono- and diglycerides and milk protein as surfactant showed that stable oil droplet size over 28 days storage at 25 °C.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The stability of emulsions can be characterized using techniques such as light scattering, focused beam reflectance measurement, centrifugation, and rheology.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Each method has advantages and disadvantages.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The kinetic process of destabilization can be rather long – up to several months, or even years for some products.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Often the formulator must accelerate this process in order to test products in a reasonable time during product design.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Thermal methods are the most commonly used – these consist of increasing the emulsion temperature to accelerate destabilization (if below critical temperatures for phase inversion or chemical degradation).
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Temperature affects not only the viscosity but also the interfacial tension in the case of non-ionic surfactants or, on a broader scope, interactions between droplets within the system.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Storing an emulsion at high temperatures enables the simulation of realistic conditions for a product (e.g., a tube of sunscreen emulsion in a car in the summer heat), but also accelerates destabilization processes up to 200 times.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Mechanical methods of acceleration, including vibration, centrifugation, and agitation, can also be used.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] These methods are almost always empirical, without a sound scientific basis.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] An **emulsifier** is a substance that stabilizes an emulsion by reducing the oil-water interface tension.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Emulsifiers are a part of a broader group of compounds known as surfactants, or "surface-active agents".
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Surfactants are compounds that are typically amphiphilic, meaning they have a polar or hydrophilic (water-soluble) part and a non-polar (hydrophobic or lipophilic) part.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Emulsifiers that are more soluble in water (and, conversely, less soluble in oil) will generally form oil-in-water emulsions, while emulsifiers that are more soluble in oil will form water-in-oil emulsions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] In food emulsions, the type of emulsifier greatly affects how emulsions are structured in the stomach and how accessible the oil is for gastric lipases, thereby influencing how fast emulsions are digested and trigger a satiety inducing hormone response.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Detergents are another class of surfactant, and will interact physically with both oil and water, thus stabilizing the interface between the oil and water droplets in suspension.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] This principle is exploited in soap, to remove grease for the purpose of cleaning.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Many different emulsifiers are used in pharmacy to prepare emulsions such as creams and lotions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Common examples include emulsifying wax, polysorbate 20, and ceteareth 20.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Sometimes the inner phase itself can act as an emulsifier, and the result is a nanoemulsion, where the inner state disperses into "nano-size" droplets within the outer phase.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] A well-known example of this phenomenon, the "ouzo effect", happens when water is poured into a strong alcoholic anise-based beverage, such as ouzo, pastis, absinthe, arak, or raki.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The anisolic compounds, which are soluble in ethanol, then form nano-size droplets and emulsify within the water.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The resulting color of the drink is opaque and milky white.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Other foods can be turned into products similar to emulsions, for example meat emulsion is a suspension of meat in liquid that is similar to true emulsions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] In pharmaceutics, hairstyling, personal hygiene, and cosmetics, emulsions are frequently used.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] These are usually oil and water emulsions but dispersed, and which is continuous depends in many cases on the pharmaceutical formulation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] These emulsions may be called creams, ointments, liniments (balms), pastes, films, or liquids, depending mostly on their oil-to-water ratios, other additives, and their intended route of administration.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The first five are topical dosage forms, and may be used on the surface of the skin, transdermally, ophthalmically, rectally, or vaginally.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] A highly liquid emulsion may also be used orally, or may be injected in some cases.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Microemulsions are used to deliver vaccines and kill microbes.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Typical emulsions used in these techniques are nanoemulsions of soybean oil, with particles that are 400–600 nm in diameter.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The process is not chemical, as with other types of antimicrobial treatments, but mechanical.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The smaller the droplet the greater the surface tension and thus the greater the force required to merge with other lipids.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The oil is emulsified with detergents using a high-shear mixer to stabilize the emulsion so that when emulsion nano-droplets encounter the lipids in the cell membrane or cell envelope of bacteria or viruses, they force those lipids to merge with the nano-droplets.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] On a mass scale, this effectively disintegrates the membrane and kills the pathogen.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The soybean oil emulsion does not harm normal human cells, or the cells of most other higher organisms, with the exceptions of sperm cells and blood cells, which are vulnerable to nanoemulsions due to the peculiarities of their membrane structures.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] For this reason, these nanoemulsions are not used intravenously (IV).
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] The most effective application of this type of nanoemulsion is for the disinfecting of surfaces.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Some types of nanoemulsion have been shown to effectively destroy HIV-1 and tuberculosis pathogens on non-porous surfaces.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Emulsifying agents are effective at extinguishing fires on small, thin-layer spills of flammable liquids (class B fires).
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Such agents encapsulate the fuel in a fuel-water emulsion, thereby trapping the flammable vapors in the water phase.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] This emulsion is achieved by applying an aqueous surfactant solution to the fuel through a high-pressure nozzle.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Emulsions are used to manufacture polymer dispersions – polymer production in an emulsion 'phase' has a number of process advantages, including prevention of coagulation of product.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Products produced by such polymerisations may be used as the emulsions – products including primary components for glues and paints.
[src:colloid-chemistry/emulsion] Synthetic latexes (rubbers) are also produced by this process.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] A **micelle** (/maɪˈsɛl/; also spelled **micell**) or **micella** (/maɪˈsɛlə/) (pl.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] **micelles** or **micellae**, respectively) is an aggregate (or supramolecular assembly) of surfactant amphipathic lipid molecules dispersed in a liquid, forming a colloidal suspension (also known as associated colloidal system).
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] A typical micelle in water forms an aggregate, with the hydrophilic "head" regions in contact with surrounding solvent, sequestering the hydrophobic single-tail regions in the micelle centre.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] This phase is caused by the packing behavior of single-tail lipids in a bilayer.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] The difficulty in filling the volume of the interior of a bilayer, while accommodating the area per head group forced on the molecule by the hydration of the lipid head group, leads to the formation of the micelle.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] This type of micelle is known as a normal-phase micelle (or oil-in-water micelle).
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Inverse micelles have the head groups at the centre with the tails extending out (or water-in-oil micelle).
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Micelles are approximately spherical in shape.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Other shapes, such as ellipsoids, cylinders, and bilayers, are also possible.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] The shape and size of a micelle are a function of the molecular geometry of its surfactant molecules and solution conditions such as surfactant concentration, temperature, pH, and ionic strength.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] The process of forming micelles is known as micellisation and forms part of the phase behaviour of many lipids according to their polymorphism.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] The ability of a soapy solution to act as a detergent has been recognized for centuries.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] However, it was only at the beginning of the twentieth century that the constitution of such solutions was scientifically studied.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Pioneering work in this area was carried out by James William McBain at the University of Bristol.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] As early as 1913, he postulated the existence of "colloidal ions" to explain the good electrolytic conductivity of sodium palmitate solutions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] These highly mobile, spontaneously formed clusters came to be called micelles, a term borrowed from biology and popularized by G.S.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Hartley in his classic book *Paraffin Chain Salts: A Study in Micelle Formation*.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] The term *micelle* was coined in nineteenth century scientific literature as the *‑elle* diminutive of the Latin word *mica* (particle), conveying a new word for "tiny particle".
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Individual surfactant molecules that are in the system but are not part of a micelle are called "monomers".
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Micelles represent a molecular assembly, in which the individual components are thermodynamically in equilibrium with monomers of the same species in the surrounding medium.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] In water, the hydrophilic "heads" of surfactant molecules are always in contact with the solvent, regardless of whether the surfactants exist as monomers or as part of a micelle.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] However, the lipophilic "tails" of surfactant molecules have less contact with water when they are part of a micelle—this being the basis for the energetic drive for micelle formation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] In a micelle, the hydrophobic tails of several surfactant molecules assemble into an oil-like core, the most stable form of which having no contact with water.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] By contrast, surfactant monomers are surrounded by water molecules that create a "cage" or solvation shell connected by hydrogen bonds.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] This water cage is similar to a clathrate and has an ice-like crystal structure and can be characterized according to the hydrophobic effect.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] The extent of lipid solubility is determined by the unfavorable entropy contribution due to the ordering of the water structure according to the hydrophobic effect.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Micelles composed of ionic surfactants have an electrostatic attraction to the ions that surround them in solution, the latter known as counterions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Although the closest counterions partially mask a charged micelle (by up to 92%), the effects of micelle charge affect the structure of the surrounding solvent at appreciable distances from the micelle.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Ionic micelles influence many properties of the mixture, including its electrical conductivity.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Adding salts to a colloid containing micelles can decrease the strength of electrostatic interactions and lead to the formation of larger ionic micelles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] This is more accurately seen from the point of view of an effective charge in hydration of the system.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Micelles form only when the concentration of surfactant is greater than the critical micelle concentration (CMC), and the temperature of the system is greater than the critical micelle temperature, or Krafft temperature.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] The formation of micelles can be understood using thermodynamics: Micelles can form spontaneously because of a balance between entropy and enthalpy.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] In water, the hydrophobic effect is the driving force for micelle formation, despite the fact that assembling surfactant molecules is unfavorable in terms of both enthalpy and entropy of the system.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] At very low concentrations of the surfactant, only monomers are present in solution.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] As the concentration of the surfactant is increased, a point is reached at which the unfavorable entropy contribution, from clustering the hydrophobic tails of the molecules, is overcome by a gain in entropy due to release of the solvation shells around the surfactant tails.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] At this point, the lipid tails of a part of the surfactants must be segregated from the water.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] In broad terms, above the CMC, the loss of entropy due to assembly of the surfactant molecules is less than the gain in entropy by setting free the water molecules that were "trapped" in the solvation shells of the surfactant monomers.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Also important are enthalpic considerations, such as the electrostatic interactions that occur between the charged parts of surfactants.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] where $v_{o}$ is the surfactant tail volume, $\ell _{o}$ is the tail length, and $a_{e}$ is the equilibrium area per molecule at the aggregate surface.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] The concept of micelles was introduced to describe the core-corona aggregates of small surfactant molecules, however it has also extended to describe aggregates of amphiphilic block copolymers in selective solvents.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] It is important to know the difference between these two systems.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] The major difference between these two types of aggregates is in the size of their building blocks.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Surfactant molecules have a molecular weight which is generally of a few hundreds of grams per mole while block copolymers are generally one or two orders of magnitude larger.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Moreover, thanks to the larger hydrophilic and hydrophobic parts, block copolymers can have a much more pronounced amphiphilic nature when compared to surfactant molecules.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Because of these differences in the building blocks, some block copolymer micelles behave like surfactant ones, while others do not.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] It is necessary therefore to make a distinction between the two situations.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Certain amphiphilic block copolymer micelles display a similar behavior as surfactant micelles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] These are generally called dynamic micelles and are characterized by the same relaxation processes assigned to surfactant exchange and micelle scission/recombination.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Although the relaxation processes are the same between the two types of micelles, the kinetics of unimer exchange are very different.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] While in surfactant systems the unimers leave and join the micelles through a diffusion-controlled process, for copolymers the entry rate constant is slower than a diffusion controlled process.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] The rate of this process was found to be a decreasing power-law of the degree of polymerization of the hydrophobic block to the power 2/3.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] This difference is due to the coiling of the hydrophobic block of a copolymer exiting the core of a micelle.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Block copolymers which form dynamic micelles are some of the tri-block poloxamers under the right conditions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] When block copolymer micelles do not display the characteristic relaxation processes of surfactant micelles, these are called *kinetically frozen micelles*.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] These can be achieved in two ways: when the unimers forming the micelles are not soluble in the solvent of the micelle solution, or if the core forming blocks are glassy at the temperature in which the micelles are found.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Kinetically frozen micelles are formed when either of these conditions is met.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] A special example in which both of these conditions are valid is that of polystyrene-b-poly(ethylene oxide).
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] This block copolymer is characterized by the high hydrophobicity of the core forming block, PS, which causes the unimers to be insoluble in water.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Moreover, PS has a high glass transition temperature which is, depending on the molecular weight, higher than room temperature.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Thanks to these two characteristics, a water solution of PS-PEO micelles of sufficiently high molecular weight can be considered kinetically frozen.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] This means that none of the relaxation processes, which would drive the micelle solution towards thermodynamic equilibrium, are possible.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Pioneering work on these micelles was done by Adi Eisenberg.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] It was also shown how the lack of relaxation processes allowed great freedom in the possible morphologies formed.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Moreover, the stability against dilution and vast range of morphologies of kinetically frozen micelles make them particularly interesting, for example, for the development of long circulating drug delivery nanoparticles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] In a non-polar solvent, it is the exposure of the hydrophilic head groups to the surrounding solvent that is energetically unfavourable, giving rise to a water-in-oil system.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] In this case, the hydrophilic groups are sequestered in the micelle core and the hydrophobic groups extend away from the center.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] These inverse micelles are proportionally less likely to form on increasing headgroup charge, since hydrophilic sequestration would create highly unfavorable electrostatic interactions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] It is well established that for many surfactant/solvent systems a small fraction of the inverse micelles spontaneously acquire a net charge of +qe or -qe.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] This charging takes place through a disproportionation/comproportionation mechanism rather than a dissociation/association mechanism and the equilibrium constant for this reaction is on the order of 10−4 to 10−11, which means about every 1 in 100 to 1 in 100 000 micelles will be charged.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Supermicelle is a hierarchical micelle structure (supramolecular assembly) where individual components are also micelles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] The stems of the primary cylindrical micelles are composed of various block copolymers connected by strong covalent bonds; within the supermicelle structure they are loosely held together by hydrogen bonds, electrostatic or solvophobic interactions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] When surfactants are present above the critical micelle concentration (CMC), they can act as emulsifiers that will allow a compound that is normally insoluble (in the solvent being used) to dissolve.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] This occurs because the insoluble species can be incorporated into the micelle core, which is itself solubilized in the bulk solvent by virtue of the head groups' favorable interactions with solvent species.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] The most common example of this phenomenon is detergents, which clean poorly soluble lipophilic material (such as oils and waxes) that cannot be removed by water alone.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Detergents clean also by lowering the surface tension of water, making it easier to remove material from a surface.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] The emulsifying property of surfactants is also the basis for emulsion polymerization.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Micelles may also have important roles in chemical reactions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Micellar chemistry uses the interior of micelles to harbor chemical reactions, which in some cases can make multi-step chemical synthesis more feasible.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Doing so can increase reaction yield, create conditions more favorable to specific reaction products (e.g. hydrophobic molecules), and reduce required solvents, side products, and required conditions (e.g. extreme pH).
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Because of these benefits, Micellular chemistry is thus considered a form of green chemistry.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] However, micelle formation may also inhibit chemical reactions, such as when reacting molecules form micelles that shield a molecular component vulnerable to oxidation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] The use of cationic micelles of cetrimonium chloride, benzethonium chloride, and cetylpyridinium chloride can accelerate chemical reactions between negatively charged compounds (such as DNA or Coenzyme A) in an aqueous environment up to 5 million times.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Unlike conventional micellar catalysis, the reactions occur solely on the charged micelles' surface.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Micelle formation is essential for the absorption of fat-soluble vitamins and complicated lipids within the human body.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Bile salts formed in the liver and secreted by the gall bladder allow micelles of fatty acids to form.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] This allows the absorption of complicated lipids (e.g., lecithin) and lipid-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, and K) within the micelle by the small intestine.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] During the process of milk-clotting, proteases act on the soluble portion of caseins, κ-casein, thus originating an unstable micellar state that results in clot formation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/micelle] Micelles can also be used for targeted drug delivery as gold nanoparticles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] A **surfactant** is a chemical compound that decreases the surface tension or interfacial tension between two liquids, a liquid and a gas, or a liquid and a solid.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The word *surfactant* is a blend of "surface-active agent", coined in 1950.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] As they consist of a water-repellent and a water-attracting part, they are emulsifiers, enabling water and oil to mix.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] They can also form foam, and facilitate the detachment of dirt.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants are among the most widespread and commercially important chemicals.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Private households as well as many industries use them in large quantities as detergents and cleaning agents, but also as emulsifiers, wetting agents, foaming agents, antistatic additives, and dispersants.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants occur naturally in traditional plant-based detergents, e.g. horse chestnuts or soap nuts; they can also be found in the secretions of some caterpillars.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Some of the most commonly used anionic surfactants, linear alkylbenzene sulfates (LAS), are produced from petroleum products.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] However, surfactants are increasingly produced in whole or in part from renewable biomass, like sugar, fatty alcohol from vegetable oils, by-products of biofuel production, and other biogenic material.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants are compounds with hydrophilic "heads" and hydrophobic "tails." The "heads" of surfactants are polar and may or may not carry an electrical charge.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The "tails" of most surfactants are fairly similar, often consisting of a hydrocarbon chain (linear or branched) and may comprise aromatic units.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Most commonly, surfactants are classified according to the polarity of their head group: A *non-ionic* surfactant has no charged groups in its head.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The head of an ionic surfactant carries a net positive, or negative, charge.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] If the charge is negative, the surfactant is more specifically called *anionic*; if the charge is positive, it is called *cationic*.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] If a surfactant contains a head with two oppositely charged groups, it is termed *zwitterionic*, or *amphoteric*.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] However, surfactants may also be classified based on chemical structure or based on their properties / their application.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Anionic surfactants contain anionic functional groups at their head, such as sulfate, sulfonate, phosphate, and carboxylates.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Prominent alkyl sulfates include ammonium lauryl sulfate, sodium lauryl sulfate (sodium dodecyl sulfate, SLS, or SDS), and the related alkyl-ether sulfates sodium laureth sulfate (sodium lauryl ether sulfate or SLES), and sodium myreth sulfate.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Carboxylates are the most common surfactants and comprise the carboxylate salts (soaps), such as sodium stearate.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] More specialized species include sodium lauroyl sarcosinate and carboxylate-based fluorosurfactants such as perfluorononanoate, perfluorooctanoate (PFOA or PFO).
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Cationic surfactants are extensively described in this review.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] pH-dependent primary, secondary, or tertiary amines; primary and secondary amines become positively charged at pH < 10: octenidine dihydrochloride.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Permanently charged quaternary ammonium salts: cetrimonium bromide (CTAB), cetylpyridinium chloride (CPC), benzalkonium chloride (BAC), benzethonium chloride (BZT), dimethyldioctadecylammonium chloride, and dioctadecyldimethylammonium bromide (DODAB).
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Zwitterionic (ampholytic) surfactants have both cationic and anionic centers attached to the same molecule.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The cationic part is based on primary, secondary, or tertiary amines or quaternary ammonium cations.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The anionic part can be more variable and include sulfonates, as in the sultaines CHAPS (3-[(3-cholamidopropyl)dimethylammonio]-1-propanesulfonate) and cocamidopropyl hydroxysultaine.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Betaines such as cocamidopropyl betaine have a carboxylate with the ammonium.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The most common biological zwitterionic surfactants have a phosphate anion with an amine or ammonium, such as the phospholipids phosphatidylserine, phosphatidylethanolamine, phosphatidylcholine, and sphingomyelins.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Lauryldimethylamine oxide and myristamine oxide are two commonly used zwitterionic surfactants of the tertiary amine oxides structural type.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Non-ionic surfactants have covalently bonded oxygen-containing hydrophilic groups, which are bonded to hydrophobic parent structures.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The water-solubility of the oxygen groups is the result of hydrogen bonding.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Hydrogen bonding decreases with increasing temperature, and the water solubility of non-ionic surfactants therefore decreases with increasing temperature.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Non-ionic surfactants are less sensitive to water hardness than anionic surfactants, and they foam less strongly.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The differences between the individual types of non-ionic surfactants are slight, and the choice is primarily governed having regard to the costs of special properties (e.g., effectiveness and efficiency, toxicity, dermatological compatibility, biodegradability) or permission for use in food.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Many important surfactants include a polyether chain terminating in a highly polar anionic group.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The polyether groups often comprise ethoxylated (polyethylene oxide-like) sequences inserted to increase the hydrophilic character of a surfactant.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Polypropylene oxides conversely, may be inserted to increase the lipophilic character of a surfactant, see also poloxamers.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Fatty acid ethoxylates are a class of very versatile surfactants, which combine in a single molecule the characteristic of a weakly anionic, pH-responsive head group with the presence of stabilizing and temperature responsive ethyleneoxide units.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Alkyl polyglycosides (APGs) are a class of non-ionic surfactants made from a sugar (like glucose) and a fatty alcohol.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] They are produced from renewable resources, possess a high biodegradability and mildness.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] For these reasons, they are widely used in detergents, cosmetics, and other applications.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Most surfactants comprise "tails" based on saturated or unsaturated hydrocarbons.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Fluorosurfactants have fluorocarbon chains.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Siloxane surfactants have siloxane chains.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactant molecules have either one tail or two; those with two tails are said to be *double-chained*.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Amino acid-based surfactants are surfactants derived from an amino acid.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Their properties vary and can be either anionic, cationic, or zwitterionic, depending on the amino acid used and which part of the amino acid is condensed with the alkyl/aryl chain.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Gemini surfactants consist of two surfactant molecules linked together at or near their head groups.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Compared to monomeric surfactants, they have much lower critical micelle concentrations.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants are (usually organic) compounds that are amphiphilic, which means that this molecule each contains a hydrophilic "water-seeking" group (the *head*), and a hydrophobic "water-avoiding" group (the *tail*).
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] As a result, a surfactant contains both a water-soluble component and a water-insoluble component.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants diffuse in water and get adsorbed at interfaces between air and water, or at the interface between oil and water in the case where water is mixed with oil.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The water-insoluble hydrophobic group may extend out of the bulk water phase into a non-water phase such as air or oil phase, while the water-soluble head group remains bound in the water phase.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The hydrophobic tail may be either lipophilic ("oil-seeking") or lipophobic ("oil-avoiding") depending on its chemistry.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Hydrocarbon groups are usually lipophilic, for use in soaps and detergents, while fluorocarbon groups are lipophobic, for use in repelling stains or reducing surface tension.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] World production of surfactants is estimated at 15 million tons per year, of which about half are soaps.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Other surfactants produced on a particularly large scale are linear alkylbenzene sulfonates (1.7 million tons/y), lignin sulfonates (600,000 tons/y), fatty alcohol ethoxylates (700,000 tons/y), and alkylphenol ethoxylates (500,000 tons/y).
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] In the bulk aqueous phase, surfactants form aggregates, such as micelles, where the hydrophobic tails form the core of the aggregate and the hydrophilic heads are in contact with the surrounding liquid.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Other types of aggregates can also be formed, such as spherical or cylindrical micelles or lipid bilayers.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The shape of the aggregates depends on the chemical structure of the surfactants, namely the balance in size between the hydrophilic head and hydrophobic tail.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] A measure of this is the hydrophilic-lipophilic balance (HLB).
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants reduce the surface tension of water by adsorbing at the liquid-air interface.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The relation that links the surface tension and the surface excess is known as the Gibbs isotherm.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The dynamics of surfactant adsorption is of great importance for practical applications such as in foaming, emulsifying or coating processes, where bubbles or drops are rapidly generated and need to be stabilized.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The dynamics of absorption depend on the diffusion coefficient of the surfactant.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] As the interface is created, the adsorption is limited by the diffusion of the surfactant to the interface.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] In some cases, there can exist an energetic barrier to adsorption or desorption of the surfactant.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] If such a barrier limits the adsorption rate, the dynamics are said to be ‘kinetically limited'.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Such energy barriers can be due to steric or electrostatic repulsions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The surface rheology of surfactant layers, including the elasticity and viscosity of the layer, play an important role in the stability of foams and emulsions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Interfacial and surface tension can be characterized by classical methods such as the -pendant or spinning drop method.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The structure of surfactant layers can be studied by ellipsometry or X-ray reflectivity.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surface rheology can be characterized by the oscillating drop method or shear surface rheometers such as double-cone, double-ring or magnetic rod shear surface rheometer.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants are widely used due to their ability to modify surface and interfacial properties, making them relevant in processes involving the interaction of hydrophobic and hydrophilic substances.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Their amphiphilic nature—containing both hydrophilic and hydrophobic parts—enables them to bridge these otherwise immiscible components, thereby facilitating mixing and enhancing the efficiency of various physical and chemical transformations.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] This makes surfactants useful in numerous fields where control over interfacial interactions is relevant.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Certain surfactants are used as emulsifiers or foaming agents in food.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Examples can be found in the List of food additives.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The alkalization (saponification) of cocoa fat in drinking cocoa powder serves to reduce the surface tension of the milk and to enable faster wetting or suspension of the semi-fat cocoa powder.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants are used in detergents, washing-up liquids, shampoos, shower gels, and similar products to increase the “solubility” of fat and dirt particles that adhere to laundry or the body in water.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Fabric softeners can consist of cationic surfactants that prevent laundry from becoming stiff when dry.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Emulsifiers are essential for producing water-in-oil emulsions, e.g. for skin creams.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] They are also necessary for a wide range of suspensions to maintain liquid drug formulations.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Plant protection products contain surfactants to improve wetting (spreading) on plants.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The most common wetting agent is ethoxylated tallow amine.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Trisiloxanes or polyoxyethylated fatty alcohols are also used.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Agrochemical formulations that use surfactants include herbicides (some), insecticides, biocides (sanitizers).
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants act to cause the displacement of air from the matrix of cotton pads and bandages so that medicinal solutions can be absorbed for application to various body areas.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] They also act to displace dirt and debris by the use of detergents in the washing of wounds and via the application of medicinal lotions and sprays to surface of skin and mucous membranes.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants enhance remediation via soil washing, bioremediation, and phytoremediation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Many spermicides contain surfactants (such as nonoxynol-9).
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] In solution, detergents help solubilize a variety of chemical species by dissociating aggregates and unfolding proteins.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Popular surfactants in the biochemistry laboratory are sodium lauryl sulfate (SDS) and cetyl trimethylammonium bromide (CTAB).
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Detergents are key reagents to extract protein by lysis of the cells and tissues: they disorganize the membrane's lipid bilayer (SDS, Triton X-100, X-114, CHAPS, DOC, and NP-40), and solubilize proteins.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Milder detergents such as octyl thioglucoside, octyl glucoside or dodecyl maltoside are used to solubilize membrane proteins such as enzymes and receptors without denaturing them.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Non-solubilized material is harvested by centrifugation or other means.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] For electrophoresis, for example, proteins are classically treated with SDS to denature the native tertiary and quaternary structures, allowing the separation of proteins according to their molecular weight.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Detergents have also been used to decellularise organs.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] This process maintains a matrix of proteins that preserves the structure of the organ and often the microvascular network.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The process has been successfully used to prepare organs such as the liver and heart for transplant in rats.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Pulmonary surfactants are also naturally secreted by type II cells of the lung alveoli in mammals.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Ionic surfactants also function as external antistatic agents to prevent electrostatic charging of plastic surfaces (ESD protection).
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Both anionic and cationic surfactants are used for this purpose[9].
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Perfluorinated surfactants, such as fluorotelomer alcohols (FTOH), are used as coating agents for textiles, carpets, and construction products to impart or enhance water and grease repellency.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] As members of the PFC group, however, they are subject to criticism because they are persistent and practically non-degradable in nature.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants are employed in water-mixed cooling lubricants (water-in-oil emulsions) to provide effective cooling and lubrication during metal cutting operations.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants regulate the consistency of ink in inkjet printers.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] An insufficient amount of surfactants results in clumping of the color pigments, whereas an excessive amount renders the ink overly fluid during printing.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] In paper recycling, surfactants facilitate the detachment of ink particles from paper fibers (deinking) and assist in transporting the ink to the surface.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Alkali surfactant polymers are used to mobilize oil in oil wells.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants also play a key role in froth flotation processes for separating copper and other minerals from ores.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants are used in firefighting (to make "wet water" that more quickly soaks into flammable materials) and pipelines (liquid drag reducing agents).
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] "Wet water" provides the advantage of allowing the extinguishing water to penetrate burning materials such as wood or fabric more effectively, thereby enhancing its cooling capacity.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Additionally, extinguishing water mixed with surface-active agents can be sprayed over greater distances at the same pumping capacity due to their flow-improving properties.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Special foaming agents (Aqueous Film Forming Foam, AFFF) for combating liquid fires contain perfluorinated surfactants that form a gas-tight liquid film between the burning material and the foam.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] This simultaneously imparts superior sliding properties to the foam blanket, thereby enabling the effective extinguishment of larger liquid fires.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants play an important role in droplet-based microfluidics in the stabilization of the droplets, and the prevention of the fusion of droplets during incubation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The human body produces diverse surfactants.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Pulmonary surfactant is produced in the lungs in order to facilitate breathing by increasing total lung capacity, and lung compliance.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] In respiratory distress syndrome or RDS, surfactant replacement therapy helps patients have normal respiration by using pharmaceutical forms of the surfactants.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] One example of a pharmaceutical pulmonary surfactant is Survanta (beractant) or its generic form Beraksurf, produced by Abbvie and Tekzima respectively.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Bile salts, a surfactant produced in the liver, play an important role in digestion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Certain caterpillars (of the moth species Spodoptera exigua, South East Asia) spit a surfactant-containing secretion at predators.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] This deters attacking ants, allowing the caterpillars to escape.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The surfactants in the caterpillars' oral secretions reduce its surface tension.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Instead of rolling off the ants' water-repellent skin like normal water, the secretion soaks the attackers.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The affected ants then clean themselves, which gives the caterpillar enough time to escape.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Most anionic and non-ionic surfactants are non-toxic, having LD50 comparable to table salt.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The toxicity of quaternary ammonium compounds, which are antibacterial and antifungal, varies.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Dialkyldimethylammonium chlorides (DDAC, DSDMAC) used as fabric softeners have high LD50 (5 g/kg) and are essentially non-toxic, while the disinfectant alkylbenzyldimethylammonium chloride has an LD50 of 0.35 g/kg.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Prolonged exposure to surfactants can irritate and damage the skin because surfactants disrupt the lipid membrane that protects skin and other cells.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Skin irritancy generally increases in the series non-ionic, amphoteric, anionic, cationic surfactants.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Surfactants are routinely deposited in numerous ways on land and into water systems, whether as part of an intended process or as industrial and household waste.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Anionic surfactants can be found in soils as the result of sewage sludge application, wastewater irrigation, and remediation processes.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Relatively high concentrations of surfactants together with multimetals can represent an environmental risk.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] At low concentrations, surfactant application is unlikely to have a significant effect on trace metal mobility.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] In the case of the Deepwater Horizon oil spill, unprecedented amounts of Corexit were sprayed directly into the ocean at the leak and on the sea-water's surface.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The apparent theory was that the surfactants isolate droplets of oil, making it easier for petroleum-consuming microbes to digest the oil.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] The active ingredient in Corexit is dioctyl sodium sulfosuccinate (DOSS), sorbitan monooleate (Span 80), and polyoxyethylenated sorbitan monooleate (Tween-80).
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Because of the volume of surfactants released into the environment, for example laundry detergents in waters, their biodegradation is of great interest.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Attracting much attention is the non-biodegradability and extreme persistence of fluorosurfactant, e.g. perfluorooctanoic acid (PFOA).
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Strategies to enhance degradation include ozone treatment and biodegradation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Two major surfactants, linear alkylbenzene sulfonates (LAS) and the alkyl phenol ethoxylates (APE) break down under aerobic conditions found in sewage treatment plants and in soil to nonylphenol, which is thought to be an endocrine disruptor.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Interest in biodegradable surfactants has led to much interest in "biosurfactants" such as those derived from amino acids.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] Biobased surfactants can offer improved biodegradation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/surfactant] However, whether surfactants damage the cells of fish or cause foam mountains on bodies of water depends primarily on their chemical structure and not on whether the carbon originally used came from fossil sources, carbon dioxide or biomass.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Zeta potential is a scientific term for electrokinetic potential in colloidal dispersions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] In the colloidal chemistry literature, it is usually denoted using the Greek letter zeta (ζ), hence ***ζ-potential***.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] The usual units are volts (V) or, more commonly, millivolts (mV).
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] From a theoretical viewpoint, the zeta potential is the electric potential in the interfacial double layer (DL) at the location of the slipping plane relative to a point in the bulk fluid away from the interface.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] In other words, zeta potential is the potential difference between the dispersion medium and the stationary layer of fluid attached to the dispersed particle.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] The zeta potential is caused by the net electrical charge contained within the region bounded by the slipping plane, and also depends on the location of that plane.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Thus, it is widely used for quantification of the magnitude of the charge.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] However, zeta potential is not equal to the Stern potential or electric surface potential in the double layer, because these are defined at different locations.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Such assumptions of equality should be applied with caution.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Nevertheless, zeta potential is often the only available path for characterization of double-layer properties.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] The zeta potential is an important and readily measurable indicator of the stability of colloidal dispersions.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] The magnitude of the zeta potential indicates the degree of electrostatic repulsion between adjacent, similarly charged particles in a dispersion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] For molecules and particles that are small enough, a high zeta potential will confer stability, i.e., the solution or dispersion will resist aggregation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] When the potential is small, attractive forces may exceed this repulsion and the dispersion may break and flocculate.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] So, colloids with high zeta potential (negative or positive) are electrically stabilized while colloids with low zeta potentials tend to coagulate or flocculate as outlined in the table.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Zeta potential can also be used for the pKa estimation of complex polymers that is otherwise difficult to measure accurately using conventional methods.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] This can help studying the ionisation behaviour of various synthetic and natural polymers under various conditions and can help in establishing standardised dissolution-pH thresholds for pH responsive polymers.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] There are several methods for measuring zeta potential described in ISO Standards .
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] These documents contain detail description of procedures for measuring electrophoretic mobility and dynamic electrophoretic mobility, which serve as raw experimental data for further calculating zeta potential.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] They also include general overview of theoretical models required for calculating zeta potential from the measured raw data.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Electrophoresis is used for estimating zeta potential of particulates, whereas streaming potential/current is used for porous bodies and flat surfaces.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] In practice, the zeta potential of dispersion is measured by applying an electric field across the dispersion.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Particles within the dispersion with a zeta potential will migrate toward the electrode of opposite charge with a velocity proportional to the magnitude of the zeta potential.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] This velocity is measured using the technique of the laser Doppler anemometer.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Electrophoretic mobility is proportional to electrophoretic velocity, which is the measurable parameter.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] There are several theories that link electrophoretic mobility with zeta potential.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] They are briefly described in the article on electrophoresis and in details in many books on colloid and interface science.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] There is an IUPAC Technical Report prepared by a group of world experts on the electrokinetic phenomena.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] From the instrumental viewpoint, there are three different experimental techniques: microelectrophoresis, electrophoretic light scattering, and tunable resistive pulse sensing.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Microelectrophoresis has the advantage of yielding an image of the moving particles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] On the other hand, it is complicated by electro-osmosis at the walls of the sample cell.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Electrophoretic light scattering is based on dynamic light scattering.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] It allows measurement in an open cell which eliminates the problem of electro-osmotic flow except for the case of a capillary cell.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] And, it can be used to characterize very small particles, but at the price of the lost ability to display images of moving particles.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Tunable resistive pulse sensing (TRPS) is an impedance-based measurement technique that measures the zeta potential of individual particles based on the duration of the resistive pulse signal.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] The translocation duration of nanoparticles is measured as a function of voltage and applied pressure.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] From the inverse translocation time versus voltage-dependent electrophoretic mobility, and thus zeta potentials are calculated.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] The main advantage of the TRPS method is that it allows for simultaneous size and surface charge measurements on a particle-by-particle basis, enabling the analysis of a wide spectrum of synthetic and biological nano/microparticles and their mixtures.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] All these measuring techniques may require dilution of the sample.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Sometimes this dilution might affect properties of the sample and change zeta potential.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] There is only one justified way to perform this dilution – by using equilibrium supernatant.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] In this case, the interfacial equilibrium between the surface and the bulk liquid would be maintained and zeta potential would be the same for all volume fractions of particles in the suspension.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] When the diluent is known (as is the case for a chemical formulation), additional diluent can be prepared.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] If the diluent is unknown, equilibrium supernatant is readily obtained by centrifugation.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] The streaming potential is an electric potential that develops during the flow of liquid through a capillary.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] In nature, a streaming potential may occur at a significant magnitude in areas with volcanic activities.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] The streaming potential is also the primary electrokinetic phenomenon for the assessment of the zeta potential at the solid material-water interface.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] A corresponding solid sample is arranged in such a way to form a capillary flow channel.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Materials with a flat surface are mounted as duplicate samples that are aligned as parallel plates.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] The sample surfaces are separated by a small distance to form a capillary flow channel.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Materials with an irregular shape, such as fibers or granular media, are mounted as a porous plug to provide a pore network, which serves as capillaries for the streaming potential measurement.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Upon the application of pressure on a test solution, liquid starts to flow and to generate an electric potential.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] This streaming potential is related to the pressure gradient between the ends of either a single flow channel (for samples with a flat surface) or the porous plug (for fibers and granular media) to calculate the surface zeta potential.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Alternatively to the streaming potential, the measurement of streaming current offers another approach to the surface zeta potential.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Most commonly, the classical equations derived by Maryan Smoluchowski are used to convert streaming potential or streaming current results into the surface zeta potential.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Applications of the streaming potential and streaming current method for the surface zeta potential determination consist of the characterization of surface charge of polymer membranes, biomaterials and medical devices, and minerals.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] There are two electroacoustic effects that are widely used for characterizing zeta potential: colloid vibration current and electric sonic amplitude.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] There are commercially available instruments that exploit these effects for measuring dynamic electrophoretic mobility, which depends on zeta potential.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Electroacoustic techniques have the advantage of being able to perform measurements in intact samples, without dilution.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Published and well-verified theories allow such measurements at volume fractions up to 50%.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Calculation of zeta potential from the dynamic electrophoretic mobility requires information on the densities for particles and liquid.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] In addition, for larger particles exceeding roughly 300 nm in size information on the particle size required as well.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] The most known and widely used theory for calculating zeta potential from experimental data is that developed by Marian Smoluchowski in 1903.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Smoluchowski's theory is powerful because it is valid for dispersed particles of any shape and any concentration.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] The model of the "thin double layer" offers tremendous simplifications not only for electrophoresis theory but for many other electrokinetic and electroacoustic theories.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] The development of electrophoretic and electroacoustic theories with a wider range of validity was a purpose of many studies during the 20th century.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] There are several analytical theories that incorporate surface conductivity and eliminate the restriction of the small Dukhin number for both the electrokinetic and electroacoustic applications.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Early pioneering work in that direction dates back to Overbeek and Booth.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Modern, rigorous electrokinetic theories that are valid for any zeta potential, and often any $\kappa a$ , stem mostly from Soviet Ukrainian (Dukhin, Shilov, and others) and Australian (O'Brien, White, Hunter, and others) schools.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Historically, the first one was Dukhin–Semenikhin theory.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] A similar theory was created ten years later by O'Brien and Hunter.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] Assuming a thin double layer, these theories would yield results that are very close to the numerical solution provided by O'Brien and White.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] There are also general electroacoustic theories that are valid for any values of Debye length and Dukhin number.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] When κa is between large values where simple analytical models are available, and low values where numerical calculations are valid, Henry's equation can be used when the zeta potential is low.
[src:colloid-chemistry/zeta-potential] For a nonconducting sphere, Henry's equation is $u_{e}={\frac {2\varepsilon _{rs}\varepsilon _{0}}{3\eta }}\zeta f_{1}(\kappa a)$ , where *f*1 is the Henry function, one of a collection of functions which vary smoothly from 1.0 to 1.5 as κa approaches infinity.
